node.text: These days it’s real, honest conversation that I crave most. The opportunity to share what makes us who we are & why we do what we do, outside of holding a camera for a living. I had a chance to sit down with @chasejarvis on his podcast while I was on the road this month. Chase has been an incredible icon in photography I have looked up to for years. If you have some time to kill over your holiday break- give this podcast a listen. Link in my bio or his. Or a quick search for ‘Chase Jarvis live show’
Of all the gifts we can give ourselves, a deeper connection with nature is the greatest we can offer.
I know where Santa is gonna be day after tomorrow. 🎅🏽

Last year today, on the winter solstice, I woke up at 3 am and rode my bike 213 miles through Big Sur & climbed 14k feet just for a training ride. This year I woke up at 9am, went to breakfast with my family and then played with my kids at the park & hung with alpacas. Different year, different priorities and different goals. I’m only sharing this because I think it’s important to realize that year to year, month to month our priorities and goals change and I think it is super healthy to allow yourself to not have such a tunnel vision when it comes to what defines us. One year I was maxing out who I was as an athlete & seeming personal growth. Another year I’m pushing myself to be there more for my family & support my wife in her goals. Both are important but obviously it takes a lot of “me time” to pursue our goals and if there is anything I’ve learned about being a father/ partner it’s that it is always about give and take.
. 📷 @snackfarmer

A frame can really bring the focus of your image to life. I especially love a good frame when the sky feels a bit empty or rather uninteresting. It’s always awesome to find something natural, but there is a lot of talented photographers who can make something interesting by simply holding up a branch or even man made. I tend to look for contrasting color that doesn’t take away from the central image itself. If there is anything I have learned from a good foreground frame is that often a good photograph is as much about what you Don’t show than what you do show.

Summer vs Winter? 
Studying this landscape in drastically different seasons really shows the many faces of Mælefill volcano. Winter creates a sundial affect from the shadow while summer is a stark green contrast when vegetation fully blooms. Which season do you prefer? 
We hoped to share the changing of seasons in my new book ‘At Glaciers End’

Personal perspective is such a valuable tool in a photographers kit. The ability to seek out a new & interesting composition despite the ease of replicating what you have seen already is a skill that often needs to be honed over time. I’ve often been sucked into going to vantage points that lacked any creative effort on my end, especially in Monument Valley. This time around I felt compelled to explore more of what it really had to offer along the valley floor & nearby mesas. .

Every two years Icelands ministry of the environment holds an assembly in which they discuss the most important topics affecting Iceland’s environment. When I was asked to speak & present my work It really validated how & why photographs can be a powerful tool to advocate for the environment. I’ve realized over these last 7 years that actually getting involved & really helping shape government policy is the only way I can feel like I’m making a difference. With my images I felt compelled to create something that was more than just beautiful photos... but also a testament to the importance of these fragile river systems and the creation of a national park in Iceland’s highland region. That is the singular most important aspect of my new book, At Glaciers End, to spread that message. 
Thanks for supporting & allowing us to spread that message on this book tour. .

Even the harshest environments can at times be peaceful, playful and downright pleasant. It’s these rare slivers of beauty that are so incredibly rewarding to seek out & document. They can feel almost like a gift after being witness to such defeating weather. This moment felt like a distant dream... not a breath of wind, almost surreal. An Aleutian volcano dressed in its spring coating.

Photographic composition is such an awesome form of expression. Walking up to a subject or landscape & finding your own way of interpreting it. For me, the confluence of these two waterfalls felt impossible to leave out. I loved the way they join together in this glacially fed canyon. Although a frame looking straight down the canyon was incredible & probably visually stronger, it was something I had seen many times before. It was still worth taking & being excited about, but I felt drawn to certain details in the image that give you a little greater sense of place & scale. Love seeing how different lenses interpret these landscpapes
.

Ever had a friend that was kind of obsessive? One track mind sorta person? For me that is @benweiland and for as long as I have known him he has been talking about THIS wave. Its what fueled his original posts on Arctic Surf blog. But despite 10 years of working together & our best efforts to score it we have always managed to just narrowly miss out. This trip was different.. thanks to willing surfers, a dedicated crew and a bad ass captain we made it happen. Cheers to you Ben for keeping this one alive. 
I figured rather than saying how grateful I am for just about everything in my life.. I would hone in on one specific thing. For me that is friendship... from the people that love you at your worst & champion you at your best. Thanks Ben for being a good reminder of that for me. 📷 @benweiland

The view from the Mesa will always be my favorite perspective of Monument Valley. Amazing how a bit of distance, some elevation & a compressed lens changes the landscape (70-200mm). It was a dream to work here with a talented crew on my last commercial assignment.

It has been 7 years in the making, documenting Iceland’s fragile glacial river systems from above. I never envisioned a enviro book being the end goal as it started as just a personal project with the goal of learning more about this threatened landscape. But today is it finally here and im overjoyed to shared my new book ‘AT GLACIERS END’ a 145 page book with over 8,000 words of text discussing the importance of a national park to protect these rivers. 
The book is available now for pre-order in two hardcover formats. Standard with a slip cover & limited edition with a hard case & small print included. Only 200 signed & numbered limited editions available. We also have included 3 golden tickets into the first preorder copies for a special large custom print. 
Book starts shipping next weeks. To get yours check my bio link or here: https://bit.ly/35AQucP .

A massive thank you to my co author Matt McDonald for his beautiful words @63mph as well as @volcanopilot for the years of friendship. Thanks for the Icelandic ministry of environment for the support as well.
If you really wanna get to know a place you gotta see it from a locals perspective. Preferably the four footed kind.
